 of their existence.
 Cities and villages built on alluvial or marshy soil, or on hills of limestone
 or lava, were obliged to resort to open-air cemeteries.
 In Rome itself these were not uncommon.
 Certainly there was no reason why Christians should object to the authority
 of the pontiffs in hygienic and civic matters.
 This authority was so deeply rooted and respected, that the emperor Constans
 (346--350), although a stanch Christian and anxious to abolish idolatry,
 left the pontiffs full jurisdiction over Christian and pagan cemeteries,
 by a constitution issued in 349.
